04459nam a22006615i 9781474470629DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222002stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744706297 a10.1515/97814744706292doi  a(DE-B1597)615440  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a781.112211 aMadell, Geoffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPhilosophy, Music and Emotion /cGeoffrey Madell. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (162 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Contour and Convention -- tChapter Two. Emotivism -- tChapter Three. Music's Arousal of Emotion -- tChapter Four. The Advantages of the New Arousalist Position -- tChapter Five. Emotion, Judgement and Desire -- tChapter Six. Pleasure and Emotion -- tChapter Seven. The Nature of Emotion -- tChapter Eight. Music's Expression of Emotion -- tChapter Nine. Retrospect -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPhilosophy, Music and Emotion explores two issues which have been intensively debated in contemporary philosophy: the nature of music's power to express emotion, and the nature of emotion itself. It shows how closely the two topics are related and provides a radically new account of what it means to say that music 'expresses emotion'.Geoffrey Madell maintains that most current accounts of musical expressiveness are fundamentally misguided. He attributes this fact to the influence of a famous argument of the nineteenth-century critic Hanslick, and also to the dominant 'cognitivist' approach to the nature of emotion, which sees the essence of emotion to be the entertaining of evaluative judgements and beliefs of a certain sort, an account very much in accord with Hanslick's position. Such an approach results either in the unpersuasive view that musical expressiveness is somehow akin to human expressive gesture, or in the view that music arouses feelings which have no specific object and, unavoidably, no necessary connection with the music.The book argues that the 'cognitivist' account of the nature of emotion is quite false and that it needs to be replaced with a conception of emotions as states of feeling towards - states of intentional feeling - whose objects are often evaluatively characterised states of affairs; however, in the context of the emotions that are aroused by music these objects are always musical events or states. Central to this bold analysis of emotion is a new account of two closely connected mental states, those of desire and of pleasure, and of what role these states have in human motivation and value.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEmotions (Philosophy). 0aEmotions in music. 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147447062940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474470629423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474470629/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK